Vice President Kamala Harris delivered a speech at the Vice President's Residence in Washington, D.C., celebrating the 32nd anniversary of the Americans with Disability Act (ADA). She expressed gratitude to the activists and leaders who have fought for disability rights and emphasized that there is still work to be done. Harris discussed various issues affecting the disability community, including housing, education, and reproductive health. She highlighted the importance of self-determination and the need for equal rights and dignity for all people. Harris also mentioned the Biden administration's efforts to invest in children with disabilities and improve accessibility in transit stations. She emphasized the interconnectedness of different movements for freedom and choice and praised the leaders of the disability rights movement for their contributions. Harris concluded by urging continued vigilance and optimism in the ongoing fight for disability rights.